What Angkor Can Teach Us About Today's Climate Challenges|https://www.yep-academy.org/post/what-angkor-can-teach-us-about-today-s-climate-challenges|was an intricate and expansive water management network, comprising reservoirs, canals, moats, and ponds. This network served multiple purposes: it provided water for irrigation, supported transportation, managed floods, and ensured a continuous water supply throughout the year. The barays, enormous water reservoirs, were central to the Angkor Empire's water system. The two largest, the West Baray and the East Baray, were engineering marvels of their time, capable of holding vast quantities of water. These reservoirs were linked by a network of canals that distributed water across the empire, supporting intensive rice agriculture that could sustain a large population. Huge water reservoirs provided the basis for a unique hydraulic system.  ...    sacred element in Hindu and Buddhist cosmology, which influenced the Khmer religion. The layout of the waterways and  ...    Furthermore, rice cultivation, an essential component of the Khmer diet and a crucial factor in the civilization's
